# Test-Driven Development (TDD) — Core Philosophy

## 1. Core Principle
All production code must be derived from tests.

Tests define behavior before implementation.

No production code is valid unless it is required to satisfy a failing test.

---

## 2. TDD Cycle (Invariant Rule)

TDD must always follow this strict cycle:

### RED
- Write exactly one failing test
- The test must describe a single observable behavior
- No production code is allowed

### GREEN
- Write the minimal code required to pass the test
- Do not add extra behavior or features

### REFACTOR
- Improve structure without changing behavior
- All tests must remain passing
- No behavioral changes allowed

---

## 3. Cycle Constraints

- One cycle = one behavior
- One behavior = one test
- No mixing of multiple behaviors in a single cycle
- No skipping phases
- No combining phases

---

## 4. Behavior Definition Rule

A valid test must:
- describe observable behavior
- avoid implementation details
- remain valid after refactoring

---

## 5. Refactor Safety Rule

Refactoring is only valid if:
- external behavior does not change
- tests remain unchanged
- all tests continue passing